Cyberattacks on the business world have increased recently.
Access to data from companies such as JP Morgan, Yahoo, Home Depot and Target caused them losses of hundreds of millions, and in some cases even billions of dollars.
It doesn't take too many attacks like this to damage the global economy.
Nor is the public sector safe from such problems.
From 2012 to 2014, there was a significant data leak in the U.S. Office of Personnel Services.
Access to welfare checks and fingerprints of 22 million employees were disrupted.
Attempts by state-sponsored hackers to influence election results in a number of countries with stolen data are known.
The two most recent cases involving the Bundestag, Germany's federal parliament, and the theft of US Democratic National Committee imails.
The cyber threat affects our democratic processes.
The situation is even getting worse.
As computer technology evolves, data protection systems become increasingly vulnerable.
A new kind of computer technology is also of concern — computing on quantum computers, which exploits nature's microscopic properties to dramatically increase computing power.
It is so powerful that it will be able to hack many modern encryption systems.
Is the situation so hopeless?
Maybe it's time to pack our vital data and prepare for a rapid digital apocalypse?
I'd say, 'Not time yet. '
Quantum computers are still in development and it will take many years before they are put into practice.
More important is that there are major breakthroughs in encryption.
For me, this is a particularly exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, when I learned about the new possibility of creating quantum effects that don't exist in nature, I got very excited.
I was intrigued by the idea of applying the fundamental laws of physics to create more secure encryption.
Today, a number of companies and laboratories around the world, including mine, are working on these technologies to put them into practice.
That's right.
We are now preparing to fight the quantum with a quantum.
So how does it all work?
First, let's take a little exus into the world of encryption.
To do that, we'll need a briefcase, some important documents that we want to send to our friend, James Bond, and a lock to keep everything safe.
Since our information is top secret, we need a special portfolio.
It has a special code lock: when closed, converts all text in documents to random numbers.
You put documents into a portfolio, close the lock — at this very moment all documents are converted to random numbers — and send the briefcase to James.
While the briefcase is on the way, you call James to report the code.
After getting the briefcase, he enters code, documents are decrypted, and voila — you've just sent an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) A funny example, but it illustrates three important elements of coding.
Code — we call it the “encryption key.”
It's like a password.
Call James to message him the combination code of the zamká.
This is called “key exchange” —
guarantee that you get the encryption key securely from the right place.
And the lock that encodes and decodes the document.
This is called a “coding algorithm”.
Using the key, it converts the text in documents to random numbers.
A good algorithm would encode in such a way that a keyless document is very difficult to decrypt.
The importance of encryption is that if someone takes possession of a briefcase and hacks it without the help of an encryption key and a coding algorithm, they still won't be able to read its contents.
The information would look like a set of random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure way of exchanging keys to transmit the encryption key to the right place.
However, the rapid development of computing power puts a range of modern key exchange techniques at risk.
Consider one of the most widely used systems today, RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it was speculated that it would take 40 quadrillion years to crack the 426-bit RSA key.
In 1994, just 17 years later, the code was hacked.
As computers got more powerful, we had to use more complex codes.
Today, we usually use 2,048 or 4,096 bits.
As you can see, code creators and hackers are engaged in an ongoing battle, trying to outsmart each other.
And when quantum computers arrive in the next 10—15 years, they will be able to crack even faster the complex math that underpins many modern encryption systems.
A quantum computer is likely to turn our current reliable fortress into a simple house of cards.
We have to find a way to protect our fortress.
In recent years, research has been increasing in the use of quantum effects to enhance crypto protection.
Some interesting discoveries have been made.
Remember the three main elements of encryption: high quality keys, secure key sharing, and a complex algorithm?
Advances in science and technology put two of these three elements at risk.
First, the keys themselves.
Random numbers are the fundamental building blocks of encryption keys.
But to date, they're not exactly random.
Today, we create encryption keys from random number sequences generated from software, so-called pseudorandom numbers.
There is a pattern in numbers generated by a program or mathematical formula in one way or another.
The less random numbers are — in scientific terminology: the less entropy they contain — the easier it is to predict them.
Recently, several casinos were victims of an inventive attack.
Combinations at the output of slot machines were recorded for some time, after which were subject to analysis.
This allowed cybercriminals to redesign the pseudo-random number generator that controls the drums.
Which in turn allowed the reels to predict the rotations of the reels with high accuracy and gain big gains.
Encryption keys may also be exposed to similar risks.
Secure encryption requires a truly random number generator.
For years, scientists have been looking for the possibility of creating such a generator.
But most attempts for today are either not random enough, not fast enough, or they are difficult to repeat.
But the quantum world is based on chance.
So it makes sense to take advantage of that fact.
Devices that can measure quantum effects can also create an infinite stream of random numbers at high speed,
that would prevent all those would-be criminals in the casino.
A number of top universities and companies around the world are dedicated to creating truly random number generators.
The first quantum generator created in my company was one by two meters in size and fit on an optical table.
Later we were able to reduce it to the size of the server box.
Today, it is the size of a PCI-card plugged into a standard computer.
It's the world's fastest truly random number generator.
Its performance is a billion random numbers per second.
Today it is used to enhance security by cloud providers, banks, government agencies around the world.
(Applause) But even with such a generator, the second big problem remains unsolved: the threat to secure key exchange.
Modern key exchange methods are not compatible with a quantum computer.
A quantum solution to this problem is called the “quantum key distribution” or QKD, which is based on a fundamental, paradoxical characterization of quantum mechanics.
The quantum particle changes depending on its observation.
Let's give an example of how this works.
Let's go back to sharing zamká codes with James Bond.
Only this time, instead of calling James with a code message, we'll use quantum effects on the laser to create the code and send it to James over a normal optical fiber.
We believe that Dr. Nou will try to hack access to data sharing.
Fortunately, his attempts to catch quantum keys en route will leave fingerprints that James and you will be able to detect.
This will eliminate intercepted keys.
And the remaining keys can be used for enhanced data protection.
Because this security is based on the fundamental laws of physics, a quantum computer or even any supercomputer of the future will not be able to crack it.
My team and I are working with leading universities, as well as the defence sector, to develop this promising technology into the next generation of security.
