How Central Bank's decision to cut key rate will affect the economy
The Bank of Russia expected to cut its key rate again.
It dipped another 0.25 percentage point, to 4.25% APR - formally another historic low.
Judging by the return of the short step of the rate cut, as well as the tone of the Central Bank's statements and updated forecasts on the Russian economy, the regulator is looking more optimistic than before.
That means the current monetary easing cycle may soon stop.
“We continued monetary easing, primarily considering that there are still risks of deflecting inflation down from 4% in 2021,” Bank of Russia governor Elvira Nabiullina said.
They are associated with significant declines in economic activity, falling domestic and external demand.
Recovering the economy, Nabiullina said, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that economic processes had been revived since the removal of restrictions due to the pandemic: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand were restored, construction and consumer goods output, slowed the annual rate of decline in transport and industrial production.
According to the Central Bank's clarified forecast, the economy will shrink 4.5-5.5 per cent in 2020 (up to 4 per cent expected) and recovery growth of 3.5-4.5 per cent in 2021, and 2.5-3.5% in 2022.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised its forecast for annual oil prices to $38 and $40 per barrel Urals in 2020 and 2021 respectively.
The central bank had previously expected $27 and $35 a barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia's 2020 inflation forecast was 3.7-4.2% against the previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The Bank of Russia's view of the economy is becoming more optimistic, bringing us closer to the end of the easing cycle, according to Russian and Renaissance Capital CIS economists Sofia Donets and Andrei Melashchenko.
For example, the Bank of Russia has consistently cut its key rate for more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has already fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
At its last meeting in June, the Central Bank downgraded it by one percentage point due to low inflation due to depressed demand and the need to stimulate a stalled pandemic and related with it constraints the economy.
The chances of pre-tuning monetary policy remain (at the next meeting on September 18 and before the end of the year), but the limit is close, agrees Rosbank's chief analyst Yevgeny Koshelev.
The combination of pro-inflation risks also indicates the proximity of a pause in interest policy easing - broken supply chains, possible cost increases due to epidemic prevention measures, and faster ( compared to expectations) a recovery in demand, he says.
In addition, the Bank of Russia's subsequent actions will require greater attention to inflationary processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility that has increased amid geopolitical conflicts, Koshelev indicates.
One way or another a key rate cut will further cut rates for the most reliable borrowers, as well as possibly on mortgages, says a senior economist at the bank's analytical office” Opening” Maxim Petronevich.
The rate correction will be less pronounced than a key rate cut, he elaborates.
Consumption rates could fall another 0.3-0.6 percentage point during the second half, mortgage rates could end the year in the range of 6.2-7 per cent, BCS Premier economist Anton does not rule out Pocatovich.
Average deposit rates, he believes, will fall too - they could dip towards 4.2-4.5 per cent in the coming months (now barely above 4.5%).
Next, they could drop as much as 4% if the Central Bank cuts its key rate in the autumn, according to Pocatovic.
