Before talking about this car for the blind, I'll briefly talk about another project I've been working on, called DARPA Urban Challenge.
The project was to create a self-driving robot car.
The driver presses “start” and without his involvement, the car reaches its destination.
In 2007, our team won half a million dollars, finishing third in this competition.
Around the same time, the National Federation of the Blind, or NFS, set a task for the research committee to develop a vehicle that can independently and safely drive a blind man.
We decided to try our hand because we thought, “Hey, what's tough here?
We already have an autonomous car.
Let's put a blind man in it - and the end of it, really?”
(Laughter) But we were deeply misguided.
The NFS wanted not just a car to carry the blind, but a car that the unsighted could drive on his own.
So we had to pick everything up and start from scratch.
So, to experience this crazy idea, we developed a small prototype buggy car to test the feasibility of the project.
And in the summer of 2009, we invited unsighted youth from all parts of the country and gave them the chance to experience this vehicle.
It was an amazing experience.
But the hitch is that this car was designed to be controlled in a tightly controlled environment, namely in a flat enclosed car park where even lanes are restricted to red signal by cones.
Due to this success, we decided to take the next big step and develop a real car that could be driven on real roads.
So, how does it work?
Well, it's a pretty complex system, but let me clarify maybe even simplify it.
So, it includes three components.
These are tactile perception, computation, and non-visual interfaces.
Since the driver can't see anything, the system must perceive the environment and collect information for the driver.
The initial parameter meter is used for this.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration, similar to a person's inner ear.
This information is then transferred to a GPS device to assess the vehicle's location.
Two cameras are used to detect lane on road
and three laser rangefinders.
Lasers scan the space around the vehicle to detect various objects: an approaching oncoming or overtaking vehicle, any obstacles encountered on or around the car.
Then all this huge amount of information is fed into the computer and the computer performs two steps.
First of all, it's processing that information to get an idea of space: identifying lanes on the road, identifying obstacles, and then bringing that information to the driver.
The system is also smart enough to calculate the safest way to operate a car.
So, we can also make recommendations on how to operate the car.
But the problem is, how do we convey that information and instructions to an unsighted person lacking the fast and accurate response needed to drive?
For this purpose, we have developed a range of interface technologies for the unsighted:
A 3-D ping sound system, vibrating vest, handlebars with beeps, a special prosthetic leg, and even shoes that put pressure on the foot.
But today we're only going to talk about three kinds of these special interfaces.
The first interface is called DriveGrip.
It's a pair of gloves with motors on the joints of his fingers instructing the driver how to steer: direction and angle of turning.
Another device is SpeedStrip.
It is originally a massage chair.
It was disassembled and rearranged vibrating elements in it. Vibration is used to communicate speed information to the driver, and to guide the use of gas and brake pedals.
So, you can see how the computer perceives the space around the car. Because the vibration cannot be seen, red LEDs are installed on the driver to demonstrate the process.
This is touch data and is transmitted to devices by computer.
DriveGrip and SpeedStrip devices are very efficient.
But the problem is that these are instructional prompting devices.
They don't actually give freedom to govern, do they?
The on-board computer gives the driver commands: left, right, add speed, stop.
We call it “the annoying backseat passenger.”
So we move away from learning prompts and focus our attention on informing devices.
AirPix is a great example of such an interface.
It's a kind of monitor for the blind.
A small panel with many holes through which compressed air exits, thus creating images.
An unsighted person can take a palm to this panel and “see” lanes on the roadway and obstacles.
Also the driver can change the frequency at which the air exits and possibly the temperature of the air.
I.e., it is an interface for displaying multidimensional data.
So here you see the left and right camera of the car, and how the computer processes and sends that information to the AirPix panel.
Here we demonstrate an exercise machine, a blind man driving a car using AirPix.
This simulator proved to be very useful for training blind drivers as well as to quickly test ideas for using different kinds of special interfaces.
That's how this system briefly works.
After all, it's a prototype car for the unsighted. And he won't be released onto the roadway until convinced of its absolute safety.
And I sincerely believe that's quite likely.
Yet, will society accept such a radical idea?
How much will auto insurance rules change?
On what conditions will a driver's license be issued?
Beyond technological challenges, there are so many pitfalls to overcome before this becomes a reality.
Of course, the main purpose of this project is to develop a car for the blind.
However, it is possible that the spin-off technologies developed during this project will prove to be an invaluable contribution to our lives.
Our sensors work regardless of time of day, fog and rain.
We can use these technologies along with new special interfaces to improve car safety for the sighted.
Or for the unsighted. Find them use in everyday appliances, in educational institutions, offices.
Just imagine: a teacher in a classroom writes on a blackboard, and a blind student can see and read what is written using these special interfaces.
It's priceless.
So what I showed you today is just the beginning.
Thank you very much.
