Russian TV series actor responds to accusations of 'promoting LGBT and feminism'
The actor of the Russian TV series “Chiki,” whose creators have been accused of “promoting LGBT and feminism,” responded to claims about the film.
The authors “understood the poignancy of the topics raised and did not want to offend anyone,” American Stephen Thomas Oxner said in a conversation with Rise.
“It seems to me that this is a story about the power and the general aspects of human life.
It has nothing to do with LGBT and feminism,” said the actor, who played the father of a boy who changed into women's clothing.
He stressed that he was “proud of the work” and did not consider it propaganda.
At the same time, the American added, he was frightening by some people's reaction to the series' storyline: for example, there was a case where “a man in deep constipation shot the set and said it was all not true.”
'Then a couple of occasions were when we met disgruntled local people who didn't understand what we were doing.
But we were open, so the people who first came in with claims were starting to help us,” he summed up.
The case of the shooting, the publication explains, took place in September 2019 in Kabardino-Balkaria: a drunk man attacked a camera crew's car with a weapon, and then he was detained by police officers.
